The Prague Stock Exchange collapses at the closing of business.
After the steep fall in the morning, the Prague Stock Exchange was able to correct the losses.
Transactions with the shares of <0xC4><0x8C>EZ reached almost half of the normal day-to-day business.
The Prague Stock Exchange started trading on Tuesday with the fall of Monday, when it fell by a further six percentage points.
This time the reason for the break-in on Wall Street.
In the Czech Republic, too, the reaction of the market to the result of the vote of the American House of Representatives, which had refused to support a stabilization plan for the financial sector there.
Fall of shares in Asia
A dramatic fall occurred on Tuesday in the stock markets in Asia, although the indices were able to offset some of the losses over the course of the day.
The Hong Kong Hang Seng Stock Exchange index lost nearly four percentage points over the course of the business day, but was later able to offset some of the losses, thus reducing the decline to about 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index, which monitors the movement of Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong stock exchange, fell 3.8 percent, while the markets in Shanghai were closed.
The shares on the Sydney stock exchange lost more than five percent, but then reduced the losses to 4.3 percent.
The Taiwan Stock Exchange declined by 3.6 percent after the Taiwanese index.
“The timing for the U.S. rescue operation is uncertain and will affect financial markets around the world,” Hong Kong Monetary Authority chief Joseph Yam said in a statement.
Hong Kong, although it belongs to China, determines its monetary policy itself, that is, independent of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as those in the United States.
U.S. lawmakers should return to the negotiating table as soon as possible, according to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, and adopt the draft to support the financial system.
Otherwise, it threatens that other countries would also be affected by the burglary.
A bloodbath of American stocks
The U.S. House of Representatives on Monday rejected the plan to support the financial system, which should be spent up to $700 billion (almost 12 trillion K<0xC4><0x8D>).
Legislators thus ignored President George Bush’s request to support the plan.
In Bush’s view, the plan would regulate the underlying causes of the financial crisis and thus help stabilize the entire economy.
U.S. stocks experienced a bloodbath on Monday, and key stock indices recorded the biggest drop in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones Index declined by almost seven percent, a similar decline it had last recorded in 1987.
The index had already fallen before the vote, but there were hardly any indications that the draft would not pass through in the House of Representatives, the index experienced a free fall.
Congress makes concession: U.S. government is allowed to pump $700 billion into banks
The top representatives of the U.S. Congress and the administration of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of an agreement on financial assistance to the U.S. financial system.
This is to be voted on early next week.
American lawmakers made a breakthrough in talks about the adoption of a $700 billion (about 12 trillion kronor) bailout plan in the form of financial aid to the American financial system.
However, this does not mean a victory.
The congressmen have to negotiate some details of the agreement before they can publish the final version of the law and vote on it.
The plan to support the financial system will be negotiated in the U.S. Congress on Monday.
On Sunday, the chairman of the Banking and Financial Services Committee, Barney Frank, told Reuters.
According to various figures, the Senate could probably vote on the plan at the earliest on Wednesday.
According to economists, an announcement that the plan will be adopted should be the first significant psychological factor for a revival of financial markets.
Afterwards, however, there is a "disillusionment" due to the complicated mechanisms of how to help the markets in practice.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
“We have made significant progress.
We have clarified our differing views on what a package to stabilize the market should look like," Democrat Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
According to them, there could be a final vote on Sunday.
Representatives of lawmakers met with U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson on Sunday night to give the government fund its final shape.
This provides for a purchase of unselling mortgage assets from financial companies, which plunge financial firms into heavy losses and endanger the stability of the entire system.
"We are on the verge of a definitive agreement on a plan that will work and that must also be effective in the market.
You have to continue the recovery plan even further, but I think we're on target," Paulson said.
A signal for business in Asia
The global financial crisis is also significantly reflected in the stock markets, which are falling sharply.
According to Nevada Democratic Senator Harry Reid, lawmakers are striving to reach a final agreement in Congress before Sunday.
This is to reassure investors of transactions on the Asian financial markets, which are in the first time zone, where a decision by Congress could affect the business on Monday.
So far, however, it is not entirely clear when both chambers of the American Congress will vote on the law, and there is also a lack of clarity as to whether negotiations at the last minute could still fail due to a problem.
Legislators hope it will be adopted in the next few days.
However, the law will undergo some changes.
The total amount intended to help the system is to be divided into two parts.
The initial $350 billion should be made available as soon as possible, as President George Bush demanded.
But Congress can block the distribution of the remaining money if it has the impression that the program is not fulfilling its function, with another $100 billion and later the final $350 billion.
Bush says progress in negotiations is positive
The President has the right to veto this decision, but Congress can override his veto.
However, despite these changes, the basic idea of the program, which was based on obtaining finance for buying bad mortgage securities, whose value has fallen, has remained, because hundreds of thousands of Americans are no longer able to repay their mortgages.
“We worked out everything.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the law on Sunday, the Senate on Monday," Republican Senator Judd Gregg said.
American President Bush was also pleased with the progress.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, said Bush was satisfied with Saturday’s progress and “appreciates the mutual effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy.”
Restriction of golden parachutes
Senate Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, the senior negotiator, said lawmakers had agreed on a responsibility for the money program, protecting taxpayers from losses, closing perks, and a schedule for funding the plan.
The new law also aims to restrict the so-called golden parachutes for directors of the companies involved in the program and establishes a committee to supervise the fund.
This is to be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
"We have worked very hard on it and made great progress towards an agreement that works and is important to the market and to all Americans," Paulson said.
The plan also anticipates help for homeowners who have trouble repaying their mortgage.
The government should negotiate new installments on mortgages it buys up, with the goal being to lower the monthly costs for the debtors and allow them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
According to the chief economist of Patria Finance, David Marek, the proposed plan is a good idea, but the implementation will be very difficult.
"It is because you do not know by what mechanism and at what price the problematic assets are bought up.
This will be critical to how the financial sector and the government divide the losses among themselves," Marek told the server iHNed.cz this week.
Whether the plan will be adopted now or early next week is not decisive in Marek’s view.
“It is much more important for Congressmen to agree to support the plan and to adopt it as soon as possible.
The psychological significance of the agreement that there will be an adoption is the most important thing at this moment," Marek stressed.
Duel on knife edge: MP3 player against mobile phones.
We advise you on your choice
While almost any mobile phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can still make phone calls.
Therefore, of course, it looks like it’s better to buy just one phone.
Despite all this, there are plenty of reasons why you should acquire an independent player.
The choice depends entirely on the type of use and the claims of the future owner.
Surely you hardly buy a great expensive turntable at home to listen to the latest album by Maxim Turbulenc.
Once such musical novelties do not appear on LPs, and from a qualitative point of view, there is no objective reason for this.
However, if you have LPs with art rock, jazz or blues on the shelf, you probably dream of at least one.
This is also the case with music when traveling, i.e. with compressed music, in simple terms - music in MP3 format.
Here, too, there are price and quality categories.
For some it may not be acceptable to spend eight thousand kroner for a player, but a pink-floyd fan will probably not be able to handle headphones for twenty kroner from the market.
Two extremes, between which there is enough space for everyone.
The selection is wide.
The life of the batteries is also crucial.
Some good music players can play much more than just music, but what mobile phones can do they don’t even create insinuatingly.
No modern device can be used as universally as the phone.
In addition to the primary functions, calling and simsing, it can play music and videos, record both, it has a better, sometimes a worse camera and maybe can also navigate.
And if you still include the smartphones and communicators, you almost have a small computer in your pocket.
It’s a small miracle, because no refrigerator can grill and no TV can photograph.
But the universality of mobile phones also has disadvantages.
However, the more features you use on your phone, the more often you will have to reload it.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy eaters.
Few phones can play music for longer than ten-twelve hours, usually much less.
In this respect, music players (especially the simplest ones) are much more powerful.
That’s why you should expect cheap phones to be able to play music no longer than a few hours.
If you still make phone calls from time to time, you would rather buy a charger for the office for safety - this also applies to more expensive devices.
With MP3 players, you won’t have this problem, even the less good ones will last at least 9 hours of continuous operation with one charge.
Another problem is when you want to transfer the music to your phone.
Unfortunately, only a small part of the devices have a USB connection, and not every phone can be connected directly to a PC without special software.
Of course, you can transfer the music directly to a storage medium, but only a few card readers can handle the tiny memory cards used in mobile phones without any reduction.
Players do not require special software except for exceptions (iPod).
You only need to feed the device via USB port with music from your PC.
Most mobile phones and players create a music library themselves, ordered by the name of the performer, the title of the album, the genre or, for example, the rating by users.
Some devices only map the tree structure of the address directory, similar to Windows Explorer, some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Players are easier to use, mobile phones can do more
When choosing a specific device, you should inquire about the life of the battery, the storage capacity, the quality and type of sound and, of course, the ease of use.
If music is mainly a backdrop for you and you only hear it briefly every day, for example in the tram, then any mobile phone that plays MP3 files is enough.
What almost any cell phone can do.
You also don’t have to control which music formats a mobile phone or a player can handle.
MP3 creates all, and most of the music you get will be in this format right now.
The format is one of the most widely used, and most devices can also play music in WMA format.
Less common is AAC (a format that Apple and its iPods use).
Better mobile phones also allow you to buy music online.
You only need to access the corresponding pages of a provider (or another provider) via the mobile internet, and you can buy a song or album.
This service can in itself be a striking argument for why you should buy a music phone.
Unfortunately, the offer of the providers is poor and is mostly limited to fast radio hits.
The prices are also not the lowest.
In general, however, it is assumed that this kind of selling of music (whether via GSM, Internet or wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most of them carry their phones with them.
If you feel like listening to something, grab your phone in your jacket pocket while the player is forgotten at home.
However, it matters whether you carry headphones or at least a wireless hands-free device.
If not, you can access the built-in speaker that almost every phone has, but only the fewest MP3 players.
Probably the biggest advantage of music phones will be the price for many.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand crowns.
For three and four thousand crowns you get a decent walkman.
The biggest handicap for most will be that there are no normal headphones.
The best and most technically sophisticated phones with a 3.5mm opening for normal headphones cost up to fifteen thousand crowns.
The advantage of the player, in turn, lies in the ease of use.
The simplest - and not necessarily the cheapest (see selection) - player can really be used by anyone.
A minimum of functions, the similarity in operation with the previously normal cassette recorder or, for example, the turntable, is obvious.
There is no threat of a collision in the form of an incorrectly employed mobile internet and a subsequently horrendous invoice for data transmissions.
Which device should you use?
Even the cheapest phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for interchangeable storage media (type M2, microSD, etc.).
Even if you buy a corresponding card, two thousand crowns are enough.
But beware.
In the basic models, only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB are usually supported.
Only the most expensive can read 8GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile phone and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, then go to Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (maximum 2 GB), you do not have to put more than 1100 crowns on the table.
Be among the more sophisticated listeners, prefer specialized phones - Walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some from Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have standalone control buttons for MP3, and the ease of use comes close to that of a single MP3 player.
The widest one is Sony Ericsson, whose phones from the Walkman series have the same user interface as the individually sold MP3 players.
The same services in the same price category of up to four thousand kronor, but with a higher storage capacity (up to 16 GB) and a long battery life (usually 15 hours, up to a maximum of 35 hours) provide you with MP3 players from the above manufacturers.
The first virtual provider will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech providers offer virtually all the services offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classics to lower prices.
Maybe he won’t be waiting for long.
The fact that the Czech mobile operators work among the most expensive in Europe, we have often reported on Mobil.cz.
By the way, this was also confirmed by the Telecommunications Authority <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which pointed out that the price of an SMS here is higher than in the rest of the European Union.
Following the final steps of the European Commission in regulating roaming fees, this is likely to lead to a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
Why are prices in the Czech Republic so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition, which really makes a battle claim.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to taunt the fact that there is an extremely high level of competition in the Czech market.
This is often agreed by the Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99>ák, who in the past had often said that there was no room for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It is likely that a traditional provider with its own network no longer has many opportunities (by the way, it would probably hardly find frequencies).
But there is one more possibility - a virtual provider.
It was precisely the entry of virtual providers into the mobile phone market that resulted in a significant price reduction, to which classic mobile phone providers also had to react.
Even before companies such as Tesco Mobile and Virgin Mobile entered the market in the UK, there were similar voices to those in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can really be successful.
By the way, it doesn’t take long to look for examples.
In February this we reported about the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to attract more than 100 thousand customers and thus become the fifth largest provider in the country.
Behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic, among other things.
The advantage of virtual providers is that you can focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need far fewer customers than a traditional provider.
They do not need relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual vendors usually stand out as low-cost companies - they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less extensive range of services.
In the UK, for example, Tesco Mobile offers SMS at least half the price of its competitors.
However, as the example of mobile gaming in Poland shows, it can also be a fairly good move to bet on a non-stereotypical target group.
This provider is specifically targeted at men.
"Real guys choose Mobilking - the provider they like and can trust," said David Seibert, the CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could also gain a foothold in the Czech Republic.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> also doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the service offering."
In the Czech Republic there is no chance, the mobile operators mean
However, it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile carrier conquers the Czech Republic, it will not be mobile.
"We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look very hopeful.
Mobilking is more likely to enter the market in other countries in our region," said Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>ková, press spokeswoman for Penta Financial Group, in a telephone conversation for Mobil.cz.
Indirectly, she confirmed that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything they can to avoid creating a potential competitor.
The GTS Novera Group has long been demonstrating its interest in launching a virtual mobile service provider, which wants to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the business segment.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed-line but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this option with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them, we have already been able to achieve negotiation progress," said Pavel Kaidl, a press spokesman for the group.
Maybe better times are coming.
Non-official information indicates that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
So far, however, this is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At this moment, we do not assume that there is room for a full-fledged virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market has large specificities compared to other markets.
So far, no subject has addressed us with a complex and serious project in this area," says Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> from the Telefónica O2 press department in his statement to Mobil.cz.
Other suppliers also point to the specificity of the Czech market.
Martina Kemrová, T-Mobile’s press spokesperson, rarely agrees with O2’s statement: “So far, we haven’t found a viable and mutually beneficial project to build on.”
And she adds: “There will be hardly a virtual provider on T-Mobile’s network by the end of the year.
At this moment, we would have to have a concrete offer already in place in order to be able to think in such a short term."
Vodafone focuses its attention more on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> says: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure.
This is exactly what we see as the best from the customer’s point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile Internet."
The responsible authorities - with the providers hand in hand
The approach of the mobile operators is easy to understand, another provider would be more competition, this would lead to lower prices and thus also to a decrease in profits.
So why should such a competitor make it easier to enter the market?
The fact that the providers can pull together when it comes to something is also evidenced by the long back and forth around the creation of U:fon.
Probably the strongest pressure towards <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> was from T-Mobile at the time when U:fon was launched.
This is also confirmed by the publicly available information from the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> websites.
Now, however, U:fon is suitable as an argument, why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová commented: "The competitive environment of the mobile market has also recently been strengthened by the entry of a fourth mobile operator.
Taking into account the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player would place high demands on the market itself and, above all, its services."
However, in view of this approach of mobile operators, the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulators is astonishing.
This is not just the attitude of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which unfortunately does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic, unlike in the UK and other highly developed countries.
It is owned exclusively by the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
This, however, related to this whole problem its very typical attitude.
"The entry into the market of a virtual mobile provider would be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile provider and a virtual provider via the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, because the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for the traditional providers", according to his response to our request Kristián Chalupa from the Department of External Relations of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
Such a wording would not come as a surprise from the representatives of the providers.
This is more than worrying from an authority that represents consumer interests and, among other things, ensures that no one abuses its position in the market.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Abroad, where virtual providers work quite normally, it can be seen that their entry into the market has contributed to a reduction in the price of mobile phone services."
Probably, however, pressure on the correct functioning of the market and a price reduction are not part of the interests of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
What is really shocking about this case is the almost touching harmony between the three mobile operators, which results from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is obvious.
Just as the absolutely same gasoline price at the gas stations is certainly just a coincidence and the result of a tough competition.
"The Authority has not discovered in this matter any indication of anti-competitive action, and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way in the matter.
None of the providers has a dominant market position, so they do not have the corresponding increased responsibility for their trading in the market.
The necessary tools for opening up the mobile market to virtual providers are probably missing from the regulatory authority for telecommunications," Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, drawn up by <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, according to which telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile operators hold a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - for the market entry of a virtual provider, the consent of the network operator is always necessary.
And the mobile operator has - logically - the monopoly for its network.
This means that he necessarily occupies a dominant position in a certain segment.
However, even if one does not go along with this argument, it should at least be a warning for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS that three mobile operators act strikingly similarly.
Complaints from a number of interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) prove that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all providers.
The transfer of responsibility to the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is then a quite common trick in telecommunications services, with which the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act failed to enforce the extension of the competences of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> to the area of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS need to know this all too well, but they probably have other interests.
It's okay if no one's looking
First of all, the functioning of any pseudo-virtual providers, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
They are companies that issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but are only partly public.
Usually these are companies that operate in the field of multi-level marketing.
Own mobile phone services offer, for example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach the chosen ones.
The joke of the matter is that the company acts towards the operator as a classic corporate customer who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he then receives special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar resale.
"If there are cases that you describe, it may be a violation of the contractual terms that we will then deal with, which may lead to a termination of cooperation with the relevant company," Martina Kemrová replied to our question about this problem.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing will not get around to the people in charge of the mobile phone providers.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned, it can be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such a procedure.
In fact, profits from the activities of these companies are not to be neglected and, at the same time, unlike the actual virtual providers, they are not affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> draws attention to possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, despite the fact that the services of these companies are only used by a very small percentage of customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card in their phone does not run in their name, so they cannot have full control of it like the normal customers of the mobile operators.”
This alone, however, would at least seem strange to the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>.
In addition, another question opens up for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If the mobile operators close their eyes to such a procedure, why are they locking themselves against a virtual provider?
It should be added that the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has quite strong competences to detect such activities, and if it does not want to do so, it does not have to be satisfied with the statement by the providers that they know nothing about them and their terms and conditions would prohibit this.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has already been stressed several times in the text, the entry of virtual providers into the market resulted in a significant price drop in the various services.
In practically all countries where virtual providers have emerged, the traditional providers have tried to prevent their emergence practically more or less.
The arguments they used were virtually identical - a market that was too small or too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the most advanced countries, however, it was precisely at these moments that the regulatory bodies intervened, which were not trying to protect the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Whether it was through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved the first virtual operator, and this was followed by more.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are throwing the whole case like a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that ambiguity in the competences is more than favorable in these cases.
But let’s not throw the gun into the grain.
If the background information is correct and soon a virtual provider appears, the Czech mobile market may soon start moving again.
If a provider allows the emergence of a virtual mobile provider, the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS will not remain idle when it comes to rejecting (discriminating) other interested parties.
And the Czechs will finally make phone calls no more expensive than the rest of Europe.
