The Prague transport companies will also transport on a chip for the first time on Wednesday
Wednesday, October 1, 2008, will go down in the history of Prague’s transport companies as a date when the first passengers will board a subway, tram or bus carrying an electronic coupon in their pocket instead of a paper ticket.
These can currently buy about one hundred thousand people who own the chip card Opencard.
Passengers can purchase a 30-day, a 90-day or an annual coupon (valid from 1 January 2009) and have it added to their smart card at the same time, at the information centres and branches of the transport companies at the subway stations Muzeum, M<0xC5><0xAF>stek, Nádra<0xC5><0xBE>í Hole<0xC5><0xA1>ovice, And<0xC4><0x9B>l, Rozadahrby, Kozkály and M<0xC5><0xAF>stek.
The coupons are also available via the Internet on the website of the transport companies www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by more than four hundred customers until the afternoon hours.
Those who use internet sales can really forget the spending window in the subway stations, where they have had to wait regularly in long queues for their paper tickets.
