The Sudeten demanded a referendum from the United States.
In 1945, the Sudeten Germans had requested the annexation of the Bohemian Forest to the United States.
This is evident from a letter that is stored in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, at least we want to live under the auspices of the United States of America.
With such a wish, some groups of Sudeten Germans would have turned to the US President in 1945.
This is evident, among other things, from a letter that has been preserved in a private archive and that is now preserved in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
The Germans of Krumau in the letter asked the American president not to allow the return of the "Sudetengau" - which was taken by Hitler on the basis of the Munich Agreement - to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation correctly and really want to be sure of the words that the American units are entering German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," the letter reads, signed with the words "people who care about the fate of the Sudeten."
Since the connection to Czechoslovakia makes the Sudeten Germans - in knowledge of the Czech national character - suspect that they would expect brutality, ruthlessness, incomprehension, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the American president to take over the patronage of the Bohemian Forest for today and forever.
"We cannot believe that, regardless of the view of a quarter of a million inhabitants of this area, you are addressing a foreign state to us, which is trying to oppress and eliminate minorities and has contributed nothing to the victory of the Allies," the letter read.
The reason why the authors are unable to sign is allegedly the fear of revenge cravings of the "Czech oppressors".
If the US president has doubts about the attitude of the Germans of the Bohemian Forest, it would be sufficient if he would initiate a referendum in the Bohemian Forest region on whether the residents would become part of the United States or want to live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text of the letter may sound a bit naive in today’s knowledge of post-war history, it does, in the opinion of some contemporary witnesses, draw a good picture of the expectations of the Sudeten Germans at the time.
Even though the Bohemian Germans had at least had to suspect that they would be negotiating their deportation from the Republic, few of them admitted such a possibility at all.
Some were waiting for the United States and Britain to negotiate some kind of autonomy for the Sudetes.
Still others believed that they could simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
This is also confirmed by the famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, who comes from Budweis.
He was used in the war as a Budweiser German in the navy on the Baltic Sea.
When, at the end of the war, he came into British captivity and was taken to a prisoner-of-war camp in Holstein, dozens of other Bohemian Germans came to him to teach them Czech.
"They believed that if they came home, the Czech would suit them," Chalupa said.
None of the German prisoners of war who had lived in Czechoslovakia before the war believed that he would be expelled from the republic on the basis of the Bene<0xC5><0xA1> decrees.
