Rats also have feelings.
A rat or a locust flees in danger, does that mean that she also feels fear?
Neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that many animals also have feelings.
But how can we check if they feel the same way when they behave like us?
The Internet magazine "Edge" has been publishing contributions by famous scientists for several years.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents a series of selected answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove this so far, where we can’t even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope, since all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, as soon as we turn to other species and tackle questions of feeling or, more generally, of consciousness, we enter rough terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it kills itself, flees or attacks.
Humans behave in a similar way, from which some scientists conclude a similar subjective experience.
But I don't believe that.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to that of animals.
On the one hand, the circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the lateral prefrontal cortex (because of its involvement in short-term memory and in the execution / control functions).
This broad region is much more developed in humans than in the rest of the primates and seems to be completely absent in other creatures.
So at least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including knowing who we are and the ability to plan and decide, there is reason to believe that man is even different from the other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity may lie in the linguistic nature of man: since such a large part of his experience is connected with language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness does not depend on language, it would certainly influence it, so that animal consciousness, whatever it may be, is probably very different from most of our states of consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine what consciousness may look like in other animals.
If, as something internal and subjective, it can neither be measured nor, because of the special hardware, analyzed on the basis of our own experience, its research presents us with great problems.
Most of my comments relate to the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more scientifically accessible.
One could study the consciousness processes of animals without regard to their contents, and that is exactly what happens with studies on the short-term memory of primates, especially with the example of visualization.
But with this approach, followed by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, one relates more to the neural correlates of consciousness than to the causal mechanisms: both may or may not be identical.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the prefrontal cortex for the emergence of visualization.
What happens to the sensations?
I attribute it to the fact that an emotional system like that of fear is activated in one of its own conscious brains.
So what we call “fear” is the mental state we are in when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) occupies memory.
From this point of view, sensations are closely linked to the regions of the cortex that characterize primates and especially humans.
In connection with the linguistic nature, fine gradations of feeling arise because we can differentiate and categorize states with the help of words and grammar in order to attribute them to others besides ourselves.
In contrast, Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that sensations from more primitive activities in the body-feeling regions of the cortex and brain stem are similar to Jaak Pankseep, who, however, focuses more on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it could well be involved in cross-generic sensations.
In purely theoretical terms, I cannot disagree with this, but I consider it unproven.
Pankseep argues that what appears to be fear in rats and humans is likely to feel the same way in both cases: but how can you check if rats and humans feel the same when they behave in a similar way?
A lobster flees in danger whether she too feels fear?
In my view, mere similarity of behavior cannot yet prove equality of experience.
Although the neural comparison helps further: rats and humans have similar brain strains, cockroaches, on the other hand, do not even have a brain.
But is the brain stem responsible for sensations?
And even if you could prove this to humans, how would you prove it to rats?
I believe that rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?), have sensations.
But I don't know how to prove it.
And because their sensations are probably fundamentally different from ours (because human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I prefer to explore the emotional behavior rather than the emotional sensations of rats.
In any case, progress on the neural level is wavering here, as long as you measure the same in rats and humans.
As I do not investigate language and consciousness in rats, nor do I do sensations, I do not know if they exist.
You might think that's short-sighted, but I'd rather go ahead than run against a wall all the time.
I am a practical emotionalist.
