Debate on bilingual education: Education in an English-speaking environment
In this issue of "Education Watch", Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the positions of candidates for bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, senior research associate in Caliphonic Studies and senior director in the Department of Educational Science at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is a co-author of the book "Not as good as you think: Why the middle class needs a school selection".
Addressing Hispanic voters is a complicated task.
Barack Obama’s proposals on education are a typical example of this.
Obama’s election campaign mentions that “the likelihood that African-American and Hispanic students will successfully complete school is lower than that of white students” — which is true.
To close this gap, Obama’s education plan specifically recommends, among others, a bilingual transitional period in education for those who are learning English first.
Nevertheless, the question to Obama is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which focuses on teaching languages other than English, contradicts his interest in reducing the gap in school performance.
Take as an example "Sixth Street Prep", a primary school in eastern Los Angeles.
The majority of students are Hispanic and come from low-income families.
More than one-third of students, many of whom are recently in the country, are learning English.
Nevertheless, in 2008, amazing 100 percent of fourth grade students passed the state exam in math at a good level.
Also surprisingly, 93 percent of children from the fourth year of school were rated as good in the English exam.
This astonishing success was achieved with different methods than those preferred by Obama.
The Sixth Street School places its emphasis on review and practice, on constant control of knowledge and an attitude that tolerates no exceptions.
In addition, the school practices the approach of training in an English-speaking environment, which is exactly what Obama should take into account, according to school principal Linda Mikels.
This approach places emphasis on the almost exclusive use of the English language in specialist teaching.
Ms. Mikels, who rejects the idea of bilingual education, told me that the school had a remarkable success with a student who had just arrived from Mexico. 12 months later you would enter the classroom and be unable to recognize him.
"It works," she remarked, "it works for us."
Would Obama take a school like the "Sixth Street Prep" as a model for other schools with a large proportion of Latin American and other English-learning students?
The school’s achievements would make the answer to this question easy, but the educational policy positions within its own party (the national picture associations have long supported the idea of bilingual education) and its own consistent support of bilingual education make predictions about Obama’s response uncertain.
While he agrees with the point that immigrants should learn English, he has recently trivialized the issue by noting that people should stop worrying about the legislation aimed at "only English."
Instead, he said, “You should make sure your child speaks Spanish.”
If Obama actually wants to close the performance gap, he should carefully consider educational models that work rather than despise and trivialize them.
