The pride and the hardships in the lives of the black people, in a city of a very special kind
Hidden among the exuberances of the theme parks around Orlando, a few miles from the glittering, noisy and gigantic hustle and bustle, lies a quiet city where the pride and complications of African-American culture come to light.
Eatonville, the first entirely black town in the country and the hometown of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as easy to describe as Hurston did in 1935: "the city with 5 lakes, three croquettes courts, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, more than enough guavas, 2 schools and no prison."
Nowadays it is a pilgrimage site.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Zora! Festival in Eatonville to commemorate the most famous author of the Harlem Renaissance.
And yet, the city that describes it – and which made it a tourist destination by including it in the Florida Travel Guide produced by the Federal Writers Project during the Depression – is and remains, in many ways, a place of the very special kind.
Eatonville is as independent, dignified and private as it was in the 1930s when Hurston wrote that rural black communities in Florida often refused to share their true thoughts with the white man who "knows so little about us that he doesn't know what escapes him."
Even nowadays, in a year when a black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, is calling for an open conversation about racial relations, many here are still tired of being watched by outsiders.
"We are very much concerned about how our history is told," said Hortense Jones, 59, from birth to a resident of the city and a parishioner of the city's oldest church.
It must be right."
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and struggle.
It is both a historical example of the black movement and a community of nearly 2,400 inhabitants where the poverty rate is twice as high as the national average.
It is, on the one hand, a stronghold of literature and, on the other hand, an example of the – sometimes condemned, sometimes praised – black culture of the rural South, which has its roots in American slavery.
It is not surprising that residents here are both proud and on guard.
And really, the concerns about Eatonville's image actually started with Zora, as everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced her hometown to the world in books that came from the heart and were written in dialect, such as "Mules and Men" (1953) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1973).
Five paragraphs in the Florida guide changed the city, which is very close to Route 77, a road that passes through Florida’s often-forgotten center, to the scenes of black history and human drama.
Naughty like Oskar both in real life and in literature, Hurston led readers to the store of Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then turned to more private affairs.
"Away from the road to the left," she wrote, "is the brown-white-painted modern school, with its manicured gardens and playgrounds that Howard Miller always cares about, even though he can barely read and write."
She also mentioned the new husband of widow Dash and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of any kind and whatever-always fits hour rooms."
In just a few hundred words, Hurston associated Eatonville with self-government, but also with illiteracy, second marriage, and sex.
This was certainly not a travel guide.
In fact, this was not a portrait that was appreciated by everyone.
“Zora described things as they were,” said 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of the Johnson girls who immortalized the Hurston, citing the men singing songs about her beauty that were full of sexual allusions.
She added, “Some people didn’t like this.”
One still remembers Hurtson as a lively eccentric who regularly returned after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, remembered that when Hurston came to the city brewed, she usually did so without warning, in a noisy Chevrolet, smoking and dressed in trousers, in a city that even today impersonates something of her venerable dress style.
According to Mr. Franklin, most residents were fascinated, whereas many despised them.
“People were always happy to see Zora,” Franklin said.
But "she never stayed too long," he added while swinging in his chair, on a rear-facing terrace overlooking Sabelia Lake, where Hurston was probably baptized.
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books out of stock.
Along with most of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten them.
Although she was once a famous author, a contemporary Langstin Hughes, and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an anonymous tomb in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she lived.
In Eatonville there was no great commemoration, no public readings on a large scale.
"I don't think they understood their contribution to the world or their legacy at all," said Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows," a biography about Hurston published in 2003.
The change came in the 80s.
Orange County authorities wanted to lay a five-lane highway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the town's slow two-lane main road.
Orlando’s suburbs had already pushed Highway 4 through the western outskirts of the city.
The proposal was made when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had put an end to the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the fight against racial mixing brought hatred into the community.
"At that time, a bunch of white boys often came and they threw oranges and stuff on the off-seat people," Franklin said.
“There was once a woman who was killed.
They threw a watermelon out of the car."
In 1955, Hurston, in a letter to the Orlando Sentinel, questioned the Supreme Court's demand to enforce integration, calling its decision in Brown's case against the school council "offensive rather than respectful of my race."
Residents nowadays say that although the abolition of segregation was positive in some respects, it weakened the group cohesion in Eatonville and the self-confidence of its youth.
"Black children were used to being hugged - I remember - you hugged your teacher in the morning and you hugged your teacher in the evening," said N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and managing director of the nonprofit group to protect the Eatonville community.
This could be maintained for so long, she added, until teachers and students were no longer from the same place.
"You didn't hug your white teacher because he was a white teacher - I mean there's a cultural divide," Nathiri said.
However, civil rights have helped make room for more Zora Neale Hurston’s – black writers, actors and artists who overcame prejudice, as she did, with positive self-confidence and statements like, “How can anyone deny the joy of my society!
I don't understand."
In 1975, writer Alice Walker set out to Hurston's nameless tomb and began to fight for the revival of her fame.
Five years later, a highly acclaimed Hurston biography of Robert E. Hemenway was found on the bookshelves, and once again made it part of the American literary canon.
The highway project came at a time when Eatonville’s most famous daughter was once again in the public eye.
And this time Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The community began planning a Hurston Festival in 1988 to show what the district could destroy with the construction of the highway.
Thousands of fans came to the opening event two years later, and every January many return for the celebration.
A few years later, the district turned away from its road plans.
"The plans for a five-lane highway animated the city, accelerated it at top speed, aroused real citizen pride," Nathiri said.
Ms. Boyd put it a little simpler: "Zora saved Eatonville."
Victory against the highway project has contributed to a change in the city’s self-image.
There were more and more visitors, such as Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who has been going to church here since 1993, and locals began to re-appreciate the past.
Eatonville was added to the National Historic Register in 1998.
A new one-storey library (named after Hurston of course) opened in 2006 on the newly paved and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
Nowadays, Eatonville is still a feature in Florida: just 6 miles from downtown Orlando, it can sometimes feel like a back alley in the summer rain, as small as when it was founded by only 27 black families in the 1880s.
(It is 90% black nowadays.)
Outsiders in search of the history of Eatonville and its significance are often still treated with caution.
For most interviews, permission is required in advance and certain things - such as the wall painting of Eatonville's oldest church, painted by a white man and depicting black men in field work - are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, such as Ms. Jones, a brave, confident teacher with a penchant for dark red, still fear that her shielded community will be misunderstood.
And yet, at the same time that the Hurston Festival grew larger, an increased degree of homeland pride was also born.
Especially young people tend to see Eatonville as Hurston saw their entire race: beautiful, with all his problems, neither worse nor better and as proud, creative and diligent, silly and mixed up as any other racial and ethnic group in America.
It is the sincere love for this city that can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin's nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in the city council or with the police, who he says might need some help.
And even the younger ones, such as Alondra and Alexia Kenon, eleven-year-old twins from Winter Park, have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people who just drive through here will think, 'Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others,'" Alondra Kenon said on a Sunday after church.
"But if you actually stop and look at its history for a moment, it's a very beautiful city."
