Drivers who may be relapsed due to alcohol levels will have to install the ‘Alcolock’.
The authorities order that the driver, who had three official penalties for alcohol levels, installs in his car this system, which forbids him to start the car in a drunken state. If he is alcoholized, then the car does not start.
The initiative was announced last month in June and is already part of the report of the Attorney General’s Office. According to them, it is a pilot project that will last for a year.
The purpose is the resocialization of the driver, which is why he receives a course for the reeducation of traffic behaviour.
In addition to the Attorney General, the Ministry of Transport and the Foundation of the Technical Institute for the Safety of Automobiles will participate.
According to statistics, between 30-75% of drivers who have been reported driving under the influence of alcohol more than once have returned to the wheel.
The 'alcolock' would prevent this because it is a system connected to the car, it measures the alcohol content in the exhaled air and prevents autostart when the driver has made alcohol test; or when an alcohol concentration higher than allowed is detected.
It costs more than 1 000 euros, the costs are borne by the person who imposes the sanction.
In this context, a study conducted in the U.S. in 2007 showed that cars equipped with these devices prevent up to 65% of rule violations in the first year after its introduction.
In Spain, it is estimated that 115 lives could be saved each year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to tackle this behaviour before it becomes a criminal offence.
And in order to facilitate their implementation, a lawful reform can be implemented in the ordinary way, and yet a fundamental law reform, which is necessary for the law enforcement process, is called for.
The device is still available in the Spanish markets, in no store, although it has already been installed in some commercial vehicles and vehicles of public transport.
It is precisely tomorrow that the House of Deputies will vote on the initiative of the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party, which proposes to install this system in school buses, which has already been done in France.
