Some children talk at night
I don’t mean those who wake up and tell us something about what happened the day before, but the children who talk while they sleep.
When it happens to you for the first time, at best you will be frightened, but in reality it doesn’t mean anything.
This is a positive sleep disorder called speaking in sleep.
It is quite common, especially among children and teenagers.
Certainly, more than one of you was told that you were talking at night.
This phenomenon can occur occasionally (once in life, for example, during high fever), or regularly (every day, once a week, once a month ), the next day the child can remember nothing.
There is not a single reason that causes this phenomenon.
Often, connections are sought with other phenomena in sleep, such as nightmares, panic anxiety at night, enuresis noctura (bed wetting at night), speaking in sleep, but there is no reason for this.
As we mentioned earlier, it can be due to very high fiber, stressful situations or overload.
In any case, this is a little researched phenomenon.
The frequency with which it occurs is very variable.
It can be quietly speaking in single words, whispering or it can be quite the opposite (screaming, crying, long discussions).
In cases where the expression is very intense, it is recommended to observe the child and seek advice from a specialist to check whether there is a problem that causes anxiety and thus arises.
We have said that it is a positive disorder, so it is not treated, whether it is, it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, with sleep apnea or with stress).
What you can do is perform a series of simple preventive measures:
Try not to excite the child before sleeping.
So, pick quiet play for the child and avoid stressful television programs that are awful and somewhat too wild.
For the nervous children who are recommended relaxations, relaxation methods can be used to help them get some inner peace.
This helps the child to sleep calmly.
If speaking occurs once in sleep, try to keep calm.
Remember that it is harmless to the child and the next day he will not be able to remember anything that happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake it up.
This is useless, because the child is unconscious, so you will tear it out of sleep.
Even though the child speaks, he sleeps, so he rests.
Remember, if it appears frightened after a pair of appearances, it is recommended to seek advice or find out what the child has reason for fear.
When they understand what it says (which is not so common), the child does not put pressure on them to conduct an interrogation and get more information.
So you will not be able to achieve anything with it, because when the child is sleeping, he is unconscious and unable to think about it.
