Hema-Quebec celebrated its 10th anniversary yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice, as Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
And above all, it has regained public confidence, which had been severely shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, the national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Donation Service were contaminated with the HIV virus and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this tragedy and public dissatisfaction, the Government of Canada launched a public investigation in February 1994, led by Judge Horace Krever, aimed at bringing light on the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and drawing up guidelines to prevent a further disaster of this kind.
While Judge Krever was still hesitant to submit his report, several provinces at the time set up a committee aimed at developing a new system for managing blood preserves in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this task.
According to the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, which is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Society to supply the other provinces and the two territories.
<0x60>1998, when Hema-Quebec started work, barely 38% of people had confidence in the blood-preserving system in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was daunting.
Through the tremendous efforts to improve the safety of blood preserves and by working in this field over the next few years, we have regained public confidence,” she says, before proudly emphasizing that in early 2008, nearly 94% of Quebec’s population had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
However, Dr. Décary keeps in mind that “trust is something extremely fragile.”
Since its founding on September 28, 1998, Hema-Quebec has acted on the principle of caution.
At that time, we witnessed the occurrence of numerous cases of the human form of bovine madness in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says this woman, who has been in charge since its founding in 1998.
“And we had no idea if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
So we cited one of the main guidelines of the reports by Krever and Gélineau, according to which exclusion measures are applied when you do not know this and when a disease progresses slowly, as is obviously the case with Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which manifests itself by degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
So in April 1999 no blood was accepted from people who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, it was proven without a doubt that this disease is transmitted through the blood.
Thus, this event has shown us that the principle of caution we applied has a meaning.
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid tests (NST), which allow to detect the occurrence of the virus itself directly in the donor’s blood, and not the antibody against the virus, as has been the case with the tests used so far.
The NST made it possible to shorten the incubation time that takes place between the time the person was infected and when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to less than a week.
Thus, the risk that certain donors might be infected without knowing, and you could not recognize, has been significantly reduced.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of AIDS transmission via blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of getting HIV-infected blood.
“In other words, it means that you would have to distribute 12 million blood cans before someone gets infected with HIV.
Since Hema Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood preserves each year, it would take more than 24 years for a case of HIV to occur.
I believe that you can feel comfortable doing this nowadays when you get a blood transfusion or prescribe it to restore health," says Hema-Quebec's chief executive.
“Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen can enter the system.
Only last year, the chikungunya virus emerged on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted through the blood through insects.
We need to monitor continuously," continues Dr. Décary, before stressing that Hema-Quebec must provide adequate care in addition to safe supply.
“The need increases as the population ages.
Because cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also affects the blood donor network, which, on average, includes only 3% of the population of Quebec eligible for blood donation.
Any healthy person who is 18 years of age or older and meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who provide their blood are not accepted because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and those who have travelled to a country where malaria is spread are excluded from blood donation for one year.
<0x60>With this 3%, we manage to get an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Lack of supplies is very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network as they get older and can no longer donate blood.
It’s hard to convince people to donate blood, but most importantly, to hold them and make them become regular donors.
“Life is so hectic these days that you rarely find the time to spend an hour donating blood,” Francine Decary said.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec delivers not only blood preserves, but also human tissue, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin, which is used almost exclusively in severe burn injuries.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before being temporarily stored at Hema-Quebec, which also manages Quebec’s only public umbilical cord blood bank.
In the umbilical cord, which was previously considered biomedical waste, there is rich blood stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“A few weeks ago we celebrated the storage of our thousandth cord blood sample, and we plan to take more than a thousand a year.
<0x60>We should probably start making it available for transplants at the beginning of next year,' explains Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood sample program as very popular.
<0x60>Many mothers believe they don't have access to it' because Hema-Quebec lacks the resources to offer this complex and costly program in all hospitals in Quebec.
