Free Opinion - The Orwellian Speech by Barrick Gold
In its September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Deputy General Director of the Canadian Gold Mine Barrick Gold.
This confirms, and follows an Orwellian logic, that the world’s largest gold mining company sought a defamation lawsuit of six million against three authors and a small destitute publishing house, with the aim of opening a ‘public transparent debate’.
If it is true that the judges are independent and impartial, then they do not judge about the truth, especially not in the case of defamation charges, but about the law.
As expected, this fundamental difference was completely concealed by Mr Garver.
For Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate is to ruin anyone who dares to represent one of their opposite opinions.
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and editors of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums of money to prepare their defense and fight with very unequal weapons against an army of lawyers paid out of the almost inexhaustible pockets of the gold mine.
The tactic in these unequal struggles is, by the way, often to ruin the defenders in order to force an amicable settlement that silences the opposing side and, moreover, deters anyone who dares to deal with the question again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, she should have presented her view of things to public opinion.
In contrast to what is commonplace in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, in Canada debates are usually carried out through the exchange of ideas rather than by batting.
So it would have been enough if the gold mine had exposed its books and files and opened up a real debate through which newspapers, media, publications and the financing of independent audit teams could have shed light on this issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to have confidence in public opinion and wipes the petitions and letters in support of the authors of Noir Canada aside with one hand movement.
Could Mr Garver perhaps explain how he can simultaneously ask for a 'public' debate while disregarding the opinions of this public?
Apparently, in the world of the Vice President, this word only encompasses the generously paid lawyers, and not the community of all Canadians; a rather narrow view of the term.
In a democracy, even slanderers have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn’t understand—or doesn’t want to understand—is that the public that supports the authors and editors of Noir Canada does so primarily because they reject the brutal attitude of the gold mine.
This public is willing to listen and judge Barrick, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, and not in a framework that many perceive as a gag complaint (in the course of the <0x60>public debate', Barrick Gold has just made a demand to the authors of Noir Canada in which she asks them not to use this term anymore...).
Apart from Mr. Garver’s surreal speech, Barrick Gold’s lawsuit is a direct attack on the freedom of academic research and truth-finding that is fundamental to any democratic society.
It completely denies the right to quote credible sources and discuss facts and interpretations that form the basis of intellectual work.
If in a country like Canada it is impossible to explore and discuss topics that the rich companies of the world do not like, who else can do that?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could lead it by following the scientific norms used by the authors of Noir Canada.
She has a right to reply.
The university environment to which we belong has long known how to manage debates and disagreements and how to resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s disproportionate lawsuit clearly shows that, contrary to what she claims, she has no desire for a transparent debate.
This is a loss for the university world, as well as for the public debate, and it is time for governments to take action to limit these kinds of unjustified lawsuits.
Rescue for Wall Street - Democrats and Republicans Understand
The Bush administration and senior congressmen, Republicans and Democrats alike, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the most extensive economic recovery plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new $700 billion version of the plan to stop the financial crisis that has been shaking Wall Street for months has yet to be adopted by the two chambers of Congress.
The main contents are: better control of MEPs over the practical application of the plan, new mechanisms to secure the repayment of public funds used, new orders to limit the number of houses seized due to arrears, and the right to monitor the salaries paid to the executives of the supported companies.
The U.S. Secretary of Finance Henry Paulson, the President of the Chamber of Deputies Nancy Pelosi, and the representative of Republicans present at the negotiations, Senator Judd Gregg, announced yesterday, a few minutes after midnight, the good news, after a two-day negotiating marathon.
"We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the market," Bush administration representative Henry Paulson said.
“Everything happened to protect the real economy and the American people from the price crisis on Wall Street,” the Democrat said.
“This is the basic point: if we don’t do that, the trauma, chaos, and unrest in Americans’ daily lives will be enormous,” Republican Judd Gregg said in a statement.
Negotiations had accelerated over the past two hours, fearing the impact a renewed failure would have had on investors’ mood.
The deadline that had been agreed was the market opening this morning.
The two American presidential candidates, who took part in the negotiations late, were more likely to be in favour of the agreement, but did not fail to express their dissatisfaction with the need to meet them in this extreme way.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama insisted on the addition of certain arrangements to the agreement, especially those designed to allow owners to keep their homes, and those relating to the salaries of the executives of the companies rescued by the state.
“If one asks taxpayers to take extraordinary action on account of the irresponsibility of certain persons, it is not something to congratulate.
But these measures are necessary," he said on American television channels.
When asked on another channel whether he will vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent John McCain replied: “I would like to know the details first, but I hope so.
“The guiding principles I’ve read [show] that this is one thing that we all will have to digest, and with which we will be able to move forward.
The option of doing nothing is simply unacceptable," he said.
The $700 billion plan is aimed at using the money of taxpayers
It comes 14 months after a crisis triggered by the bursting of a real estate bubble that initially led to the collapse of high-risk mortgage loans (subprime) before expanding to further forms of more common bonds (PCAAs), and finally to a freezing of financial power and to the ruin of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republican MPs who failed the first attempt to reach an agreement last week.
Since the Democrats have accepted that certain "toxic" assets of the societies in distress should be secured only by the government and not bought, it is believed to escape the deadlock.
To round off the perspectives for everyone in Congress, an order has also been added that if the government loses with this program within five years, it can then levy new taxes in order to recover its invested capital.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first sum of 250 billion, to which another 100 billion can be added if the president considers it necessary.
The payment of another 350 billion dollars must be approved by Congress in a renewed vote.
In return for his help, Washington receives shares in the supported companies, which will earn dividends in the event of profits, and which it can resell once the storm has passed.
The Federal Government will have the opportunity to suspend the seizure procedures relating to the dwellings linked to the real estate loans affected by this plan, as well as to set deadlines for repayment and severance payments to the executives of the companies concerned.
The developers of the plan would like the Chamber of Deputies to vote on it today, and the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will get the green light.
In fact, yesterday, more votes were raised against this plan, both on the part of the Republicans and the Democrats.
“Washington obviously doesn’t understand us,” Republican Scott Garett, a member of the chamber’s finance committee, told his voters.
“Yes, we have a big financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
