The Psychology of Overbidding - or Why We're Ready to Pay More
In auctions, buyers tend to spend more and thus overvalue the filed.
Neurologists and economic researchers at the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological-economic foundations of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in "Science" magazine, people do not want to give up in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even excessive prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers was to play the lottery while the other took part in a playful action - in both cases, the subjects' active brain regions were examined using functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games, participants were able to win money, but increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the cerebral cortex, was measured in losers at the auction, where overbidding the opponent plays an essential role.
Among many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the “self-rewarding” of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore believed that the price increase could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of the striatum.
To substantiate their thesis, the economists in the research group have additionally carried out research to track the money.
In this case, three groups should bid against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, after which they made their deployments.
Another group was also promised a $15 reward in case they emerged as winners of the game.
The third group received $15 before the auction, which were also lost in the event of a losing game.
So the difference between the two groups was simply that the emphasis was on winning while the other was on losing.
As proof of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, however, the members of the "against losing" group were ready for higher stakes than those in the control or "win" group.
“These findings cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
These have justified the behaviors observed at auctions so far only with the joy of winning or risk avoidance.
The contradiction between these two theories was resolved thanks to imaging neurological procedures, so we now have a third explanation ready," said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When to see the doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected people is estimated to be one hundred thousand in this country, but only seven thousand are treated, which is due to the fact that patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver disease caused by various viruses.
Symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and diseases differ from each other.
Depending on the pathogen, the hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: in hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example, through contaminated food or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted through blood and other body fluids (such as sperm, vaginal secretion or saliva).
Travellers are recommended to be vaccinated against viruses A and B, because there is no vaccine against virus C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear about two-three weeks after eating the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After that, the jaundice occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the stool becomes light, the urine dark, and the recovery can last up to two-three weeks.
Worldwide, about 1 million people die each year from the far more serious diseases caused by hepatitis B, such as liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that, according to estimates, only one in ten people infected is in drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: untreated, it can lead to liver cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, because the pathogen insidiously destroys the liver cells - in many cases, the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular check-ups, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease is more common: those who underwent a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattoos.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease can already be detected in a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to visit the general practitioner at the first signs of unknown origin.
Detected in time, the disease can be cured, the virus can be eradicated, thereby eliminating the risk of infection and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30th is the World Day of Hepatitis, held in 2004 for the first time by patient representations worldwide.
The aim of the action is to increase awareness of this chronic liver inflammation caused by viruses, its development and the importance of early detection.
