Recent research shows that religious faith acts like a kind of “pain remedy” that is said to have already facilitated the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University have conducted an interesting experiment: it has been investigated to what extent faith in God affects man's sense of pain, the British newspaper "Telegraph" reported.
In the course of the rather bizarre investigation, 12 believers and atheists each received electric shocks while studying a painting of the Mother of God.
As the results showed, the believers were able to eliminate the majority of the pain.
Using brain scan technology, it was even possible to prove that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for pain regulation.
The study was the first in a research project in which, in addition to scientists, philosophers and theologians from various departments of the university participate.
During the experiment, a sparkling device was attached to the left hand, which gave off the electric shocks.
Participants were asked to focus heavily on two paintings: on the one hand a picture of the Mother of God, painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century, and on the other Leonardo da Vinci's "Lady with the Hermine".
The researchers hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would evoke a kind of religious trance among the faithful while choosing da Vinci’s painting, as it was hardly different from other paintings and felt reassuring.
The subjects spent half an hour each in an MRI scanner and received a total of 20 electric shocks in four stages during that time, while they were supposed to look at either the religious or the other painting.
The Catholics reported that they felt “safe” at the sight of the Mother of God, as if they were “cared for,” and they felt “calm and peace.”
While viewing the religious painting, they reported 12% less pain than if they had Leonardo’s work in mind.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the experiment, said that you could produce similar effects with other, strong-acting images also among the atheists, you would only have to find the corresponding photo.
"We would have to find a picture that triggers very positive sensations, such as a mother or a father," the psychologist said.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
"Practicing the faith should change our personality, and it does so in many cases," said Wright.
After these excellent results, there remains only the question of what effect a Madonna image of Leonardo or another comparable painter would have on the pain regulation of the faithful.
Would the high-quality Virgin Mary achieve even better results?
