Intelligent car imitates the flight of the bumblebee
What would be the best way to develop new technologies for accident prevention, if not to imitate the obstacle sensors from nature?
For example, the bees.
At CEATEC in Japan, an amazing project was presented, in which Nissan engineers were inspired by bumblebees in creating new accident prevention systems.
In collaboration with Tokyo University, Nissan has built the BR23C auto-robot-controlled biomimetic system, a mini car equipped with the characteristics of bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In flight, each bee forms its own oval "private area," which is very similar to our own "protection shield," Kazuhhiro Doi, product manager for technology PR and research development, said at the exhibition.
The composite eye of the bee, which can see in any direction and at an angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role in this.
To mimic the function of the composite eye, the researchers took up the idea of the laser-controlled rangefinder.
It identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C in a 180-degree field of view within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor on board, which immediately initiates the collision-avoiding process.
The obstacle is recorded in fractions of a second, and the car robot immediately changes course, similar to the movement of the bees, by turning the tires at the corresponding angle.
In contrast to previous systems, this maneuver takes place purely instinctively.
"If it wasn't, the car robot wouldn't be able to respond fast enough to avoid the obstacles," said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the car robot project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the shield - a layer within which accidents are currently considered unavoidable.
The whole process must reflect the behavior of bees when they avoid other bees.
And that has to happen in a fraction of a second.
However, in contrast to the bees, the deflection cannot take place up, down, or even diagonally - it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction of the maneuverability of the tires.
While there are endless possibilities for the bees to avoid other bees, the researchers could only use the rotational movement, or acceleration and deceleration, in the car robot.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and more energy efficient, and therefore have a longer lifespan than conventional lithium-ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it depends on the instinctive, intelligent response, and less on the processing of the data, and even less on the ability to store it.
This device only needs to process a few inputs per second and respond to them accordingly.
It does not have to store them, or use previous maneuvers to produce an intuitive, logical response, so that it continuously uses only a handful of KB memory.
It does not require gigabyte and megabyte-heavy memories.
This is the first step in the development of the instant collision prevention technology, which Nissan estimates will be in production as standard within the next ten years.
Another application the technology could find in GPS satellite navigation by consciously steering the driver around obstacles and thus guiding him to his destination.
