Járóka also stressed that education is a fundamental human right, which would play a key role in enforcing other human rights.
Investing in the early education of Roma children can strengthen the economy of EU member states.
MEPs believe it is important that the widest possible circle of people - Roma and non-Roma - should be aware of this.
The sooner a Roma student starts school, the more their chances of becoming a productive member of the labour market increase; and through income and sales tax they make their contribution to national spending.
"As citizens of the Union, Roma must be guaranteed the right to a high-quality education - poor and segregated education must be stopped," says Lívia Járóka.
MEPs have stated that a common, targeted and action-oriented approach by the European Union is necessary to accelerate the process of desegregation in the education sector, which requires proper compliance with the existing and planned anti-discrimination directives.
“We need to break the vicious cycle of poverty, segregation and unemployment and give Roma children the democratic opportunities to contribute to the future of Europe as full-fledged citizens,” Járóka said.
