The much criticized duo, however, already showed that they do not want to stick on their armchairs.
In doing so, they want to appease the angry faction and the party base, which demanded personal consequences one day after the "Bavarian tsunami" in the face of the loss of the absolute majority.
Five years ago - admittedly, under the leadership of Edmund Stoiber, who is at his career’s peak - the Christian Social Union still reached 60.7 percent, but now, a year after the coup against Stoiber, they were only able to secure 43.4 percent of the vote.
For 46 years, the CSU was a “single-government” in Bavaria, which generates 18 percent of Germany’s GDP.
While the conservatives remain the determining force in the southern federal state, which is also important for the Hungarian economy, they will have to govern in a coalition in the future.
As a first sign of the party-internal restructurings, the potential successor of Huber, Vice-President and Federal Agriculture Minister Horst Seehofer, will also be involved in the exploration team, which is conducting exploratory talks with the liberal FDP and the right-wing “free voters” on a possible Munich coalition.
The irony of fate is that with the list of "free voters" Gabriele Pauli enters the legislature, whose anti-stoiber appearance the Huber-Beckstein duo first took advantage of, and then mercilessly deprived the determined politician.
The CSU leadership is now concentrating all its forces on stabilizing Beckstein.
In this transitional process, Stoiber, who has so far pulled the strings out of the background, will play an active role. The former prime minister and CSU chairman called September 28 the "bitterest day of his political career".
On Monday, Huber made a few poisonous remarks towards the CDU - in his view, the CSU would have deserved far more support from the sister party.
Other CSU politicians interpreted the defeat as a signal to the CDU and thus also to Angela Merkel.
If the CSU, which contributed a lot to the success at national level in 2005, is not put back on its feet with a joint act of strength, Merkel cannot become Chancellor again after the German parliamentary elections in September 2009.
Merkel, who has made no secret of her disappointment at the fiasco, believes that the loss of ground by the CSU will not have a negative impact on the big coalition in Berlin.
However, what is relative is that the wounded CSU will not be easier to govern, and the crisis of the Social Democrats continues.
With 18.6 percent, the SPD achieved its best result in Bavaria since 1946.
Lukashenko opposition: 110-0
In the elections on Sunday, no member of the opposition has made it to the Ukrainian parliament.
Russian observers believe this is due to the prosperity and stability in the country led by Alexander Lukashenko, but the OECD suspects illegality in the counting of votes.
The OECD, which has sent 450 observers from 43 countries, has not recognised the elections.
Although the legislature of the 10-million-populated state has been without opposition for decades, the opposition party, assembled under the name of "United Democratic Forces" (ODS), since yesterday's elections, sincerely hoped that Lukashenko, who would allow in the unclean elections and thanks to a constitutional amendment in 2006, would renew his presidential mandate in the parliament for the fourth time.
That is why the ODS has even withdrawn from the previously planned boycotts.
Ukraine is becoming more and more economically dependent on Russia’s natural gas imports thanks to rising prices. Loans have even been taken to alleviate price increases, and the country has also agreed to the sale of Beltransgas, the owner of the country’s leading gas pipeline, to the Russians. In the background of the opposition’s expectations, there was the hope that Ukraine wanted to improve its relationship with the EU because of anti-Lukashengmoor
The OECD election evaluation report, which emphasized the positive movements rather than the shortcomings, such as the exclusion of one third of opposition candidates from the elections, provided a temporary relaxation.
However, the OECD's quick report criticized the campaign on Monday - according to which opposition members should not appear in the press - and in particular the fact that the opposition was not allowed to be present in the counting of the votes.
Despite all this, the opposition is able to see an improvement in the political system: political prisoners have been set free, for example, and Minsk is even ready for minor confrontations with Moscow by continuing to deny recognition of the independence of the renegade Georgian provinces of South Ossetia and Abkhazia, although Russia, with which Ukraine is considered on paper a federal state, has been considering the two territories as independent for a month.
"We have taken two steps forward and one backward, but the most important thing is that the dialogue between Belarus and the EU has begun," Alexander Milinkevich told our newspaper.
According to the opposition candidate of the 2006 presidential election, a continuation is desirable, although "the powerful have become afraid to let even one opposition member in parliament."
The opposition does not plan any protest measures in view of the results, but rather tries to make the need for economic reform clear to the voters.
"We are struggling with many problems here - the opposition newspapers have to be printed in Russia, the local authorities are putting stones in our way when distributing them, but nevertheless I see that more and more people are supporting change, even the older ones" - said Milinkevich, alluding to the fact that not even the most supported layer of pensioners agrees with the Lukashenko regime, whose sole security is the production.
“Thanks to the country’s indebtedness and the increase in the trade deficit, it is only a matter of time before the ‘social security’, which reminds of the silence of a cemetery, begins to crumble,” Milinkevich said.
Unlike opposition politicians, Russian observers have described the elections as democratic.
Sergei Lebedev, head of the mission of the Community of Independent States, told the news agency Ria Novosti: "People believe in deeds, not words, and the absence of opposition is therefore proof of the maturity of Belarusian voters.
Brunetta: "From now on, breakfast will be served before work"
For the first time in the history of Palazzo Chigi, there are rotating doors for the entrances and exits of the officials.
As of today, the measure will come into force against those clever people who first stamp and then go for coffee during working hours.
The new anti-lazyness law was presented today by Renato Brunetta, Minister of Public Administration, and Mauro Masi, Secretary General of the Bureau of the Council of Ministers.
