Napolitano: "Prevention of accidents at work is crucial"
Every day in Italy, 2,500 workplace accidents occur, three people die and 27 remain disabled for life.
For 2007, the data from the Inail (Istituto nazionale contro gli infortuni sul lavoro) confirm that the fatal accidents at work were around 1200.
These numbers prove the gravity of a phenomenon that causes almost twice as many deaths as murders.
Today, the Anmil (Associazione Nazionale Mutilati e Invalidi del Lavoro) in all the provinces of Italy will celebrate the 58th National Day for Victims of Work Accidents in order to draw the attention of social institutions and media to this dramatic situation.
"The worrying data spread by Anmil and the tragic news these days confirm how crucial the issue of prevention at the workplace is," the President of the Republic Giorgio Napolitano confirms in his message to the President of the Amil (Associazione nazionale mutilati ed invalidi del lavoro) Pietro Mercandelli.
The head of state expresses his "great appreciation for the constant commitment to prevention in the workplace, to protect the injured workers, to assist the families of the victims and to raise public opinion."
"An outraged 'basta' has risen up; understandable in tragedies that, measured by their magnitude, trigger some media turmoil and public sympathy. But everyday reality often confronts us with dramatic events that can even repeat themselves in their own dynamics."
Napolitano does not hide that "there is definitely a resource problem: it must be invested decisively in education and information."
The numerous initiatives for a more direct awareness in schools on the part of young people who nourish the world of work are of particular importance.
It is our duty to pay attention to this phenomenon and not to distract from its social gravity; it is our duty to enforce and improve a legislative norm.
For his part, the President of the Chamber, Gianfranco Fini, stressed "how the phenomenon of work-related deaths constitutes an urgent social emergency that offends the conscience of all of us and forces all institutions to work towards decisive rules aimed at putting an end to the problem".
"The data on accidents at work seem to indicate a slight improvement, but this does not exclude the fact that the number of deaths related to work is far too high," said Pietro Mercandelli, President of Anmil.
"We don't want this 'positive tendency' to mean less attention. That's what causes the tragedy in the end."
"How do you believe that you are basically doing too little to counteract the phenomenon of accidents. You can fight against it through various actions.
In our opinion, stronger controls and inspections are necessary – according to Mercandelli; but also stronger measures to educate workers who start at school.”
"A further effort is needed - he adds - in terms of communication and public opinion awareness.
But above all, a greater sense of responsibility on the part of employers towards a phenomenon that constitutes a social emergency is in demand."
Mercandelli also spoke of "the progressive deterioration of protection for work accident victims" and denounced the "abolition of the social system against which we have been fighting in recent years."
"The aim is, therefore, to return to the worker a guarantee on insurance so that the fate of the victim of a work accident does not depend on voluntary or accidental donations decided from time to time by a legislator".
MP3 player under prosecution: risk of hearing damage
Listening to loud music over a longer period of time with portable music devices, such as MP3 players, can lead to permanent hearing loss.
This is reported by the European Commission, which in a report published today in Brussels cites the opinion of the EU’s Csrseri (scientific committee on current and recently identified health risks).
"The report - it says in a note - makes it clear that 5-10% of those who listen to loud music with portable music devices for at least five years a week for more than one hour a day risk permanent loss of their hearing."
"I'm worried that such a large number of teenagers, who usually put portable music devices and mobile phones at high volume, will irretrievably damage their hearing without knowing it," said Meglena Kuneva.
"The scientific findings - it is said by the EU - show a clear risk, which urges to act quickly.
What really matters is to raise awareness among consumers and make this information a common good.
In view of these scientific findings, we need to re-examine the existing control systems so that they are fully effective and keep up with the new technology."
Brussels had commissioned the independent scientific committee in view of the widespread use of portable music devices among young people.
"The scientists - concludes the EU communication - confirm that they are rightly concerned and that the EU Commission, together with the other EU Member States and those concerned, will now examine the necessary measures to better protect children and young people from the noise coming from portable music devices and similar devices."
There is already a European standard that limits the level of noise of portable music equipment to 100 dB. The concern about the damage that could come from too much noise pollution.
One can very well limit these damages by resorting to solutions such as the reduction of the volume and the length of the noise exposure.
In its report, the EU Scientific Committee points out that if users of portable music devices listen to loud music (no less than 89 decibels) five hours a week, the legal limits on the maximum noise level at the workplace have already been exceeded.
Those who cross that line of music risk the complete loss of hearing within five years.
This represents 5-10% of the users of such devices, the number of which can be estimated to be between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
Roma, Alemanno launches the "Commission for the Future of the Capital"
We start today, in March it is supposed to be over, in June we will take stock.
This is the procedure laid down by the Capitol for the work of the "Commission for the Future of the Capital Rome", which met this morning in the new headquarters behind the Caracalla thermal baths.
In six months, President Marzano and the other 49 members of the Commission will work out the guidelines for Rome.
Once the project is completed, the City Council and the Municipal Council will evaluate the analyses and projects in order to be able to present the strategic plan for Rome in June with the "official stamp" of the Capitol and the Mayor Gianni Alemanno.
"The Commission is absolutely independent and all political, social and cultural opinions are represented in it", - stresses Alemanno. "It will present proposals for a development plan for Rome, whose political leaders remain the city council and the municipal council.
There is no redistribution of responsibilities, only the will to have a place where one can develop a large project for Rome.
Its task will be completed in March and the Commission will disintegrate, as such a project must have a deadline.
In June - the mayor announces - we will present the strategic plan, in which we will take advantage of the work done by the Commission."
Those who question the Commission's competence because of its lack of commitment, Alemanno replies: "Everything depends on the work that the Commission will do and on the quality of its proposals.
If, as in France, the Attali Commission delivers quality results – and this will certainly be the case in Rome – then its contribution will be fundamental.
Too often politics deals with the everyday problems and emergencies that occur from time to time.
We, on the other hand, want to have a longer period in view in order to work seriously on the development of Rome and the future of the city in a deeper perspective."
"This commission is neither a useless institution nor a wreck: it is absolutely free, it will not cost the Roman citizens a penny and it will make us think, it will employ the best minds of the capital."
According to Alemanno, "it is necessary to have a strategic plan that is neither hermetic nor static in order to enable our city to take a quality leap - which it really needs - and thus to take a joint step into the future."
A future, says the mayor of Rome, which "will not only limit itself to the current municipal boundaries, but will look much further", not only in terms of Rome's role as a metropolis and political capital of Italy, but also as the future capital of Europe and the Mediterranean."
