The elite is in danger.
The phenomenon had already been revealed a few days ago when the Chamber of Deputies voted against the White House’s $700 billion savings package: A large proportion of Americans were and are more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This is confirmed by yesterday’s issue of the New York Times, which reports how the crisis is dividing the Republican Party, which is increasingly splitting into its old and moderate East Coast soul, which has always favored the state institutions and the business community, and which is hostile to those neoconservatives who are “those in Washington” and the financial world, and which is gaining power mainly in the south and the center of the states.
This part of the party owes its rise above all to the voice of the one I mentioned above.
However, this example just mentioned is only a small part of the major changes that the current economic earthquake is announcing or even already represents: not only in the US, but also throughout the West and perhaps beyond will be affected by them.
Both in the states and in Europe, the crisis seems to accelerate the long feared events, which are finally taking shape and coming to light under these new conditions.
The first of these phenomena is the new discovery, the unprecedented renaissance of the state in conjunction with a kind of renationalization of the economy.
In fact, the crisis means a decline of banking and financial institutions, which have close ties to foreign countries and at the same time manage an enormous amount of the assets of private households living in a single state.
This represents an immediate political problem for the governments: namely, how to behave towards the affected families, which are also a huge voter base.
So the crisis seems economically global, politically, on the other hand, it is almost purely national.
Political internationalism in itself seems to have fallen aside and lost its right to speak: the obvious proof of this has been given by the EU, which, due to its division into various national and international conflicts, cannot find a common path.
Therefore, everyone now expects the intervention of their own state; rescue plans, new rules, and especially distribution of aid funds: Since the crisis became more and more serious, only the US is in the economic situation to save themselves without outside help.
And in addition to the means, they also have the legitimacy to use them: thus, two prerequisites not to be overestimated – under certain circumstances – to which no international organization and no market will otherwise be able to rely in a similar way.
That new emphasis placed on the state-national element is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the ever-increasing importance which has recently been associated in the economy with a closely related sector: territoriality.
Paradoxically, now that we have been so convinced that we have long since entered a networked realm, a realm of always differentiated technologies, of the intangible, that we must suddenly see how our future will depend more and more on the essential material things: water, harvest and oil.
These can certainly all be transported from one place to another in the world, but are nevertheless connected to the utmost with a narrowly defined piece of earth – a territory.
Therefore, the person who has such a territory is in advantage over another who lives in a harvestless, waterless or oil-free area.
I now come to the second novelty, which, however, requires a brief introduction.
Whoever says territory, whoever says government, whoever says politics, also says leadership.
In this sense, the financial crisis seems to be generating two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, there is the knowledge of the need for respected leadership, that is, the need for someone who knows how to regulate things.
On the other hand, there is now a wave of indignation at the existing leaderships, especially those of the economy, which have turned out to be inadequate and full of shadow zones.
Finally, there is a deeper and in a sense even more disturbing aspect: a loss of confidence, an intolerance, an image of inappropriateness, a sense of distance, all directed at a whole class of managers of Western countries.
It seems to be the conviction among large sections of the population that it is not only the actions of the social elite, but already their world of ideas, their way of life, their culture in the broadest sense of the word, whose content presents itself to the majority as ever more foreign and traditional.
The demand for leadership thus feeds underground a branched but powerful movement of disempowerment of the leading class and the traditional political establishment. This is manifested in unforeseen "revolts" of the voters and perhaps in the sudden reversal of the American collective mood of recent times: starting with the rise of the conservatives in Austria and Bavaria, the right also plays a role in this country.
One gets the impression that the old elite, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, magazines, intellectual believers, some would say their format, more and more understanding problems and therefore less representative value in relation to what is happening today in the lower social classes of the West and is intensified by the financial crisis and driven to overdimensionality.
In the face of all this, it would be simply exaggerated to speak of a “rebellion of the masses”.
Keeping your eyes wide open is certainly not.
The super glue that goes up against the walls
Defeat the forces of gravity thanks to an adhesive and be able to climb up walls like Superman.
This is the subject of four American research centres, one of which seems to have almost reached its goal.
Using an adhesive applied on an area of only 2.5 sqcm, the researchers have succeeded in fixing a body weighing 100 kg on a vertical wall.
The STUDIO – an American journal has published the results of researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material invented by the research team is a further development of the already used adhesives, which use a special carbon structure, called carbon nanotubes.
"The principle of adhesive can be imagined as a row of spaghetti tubes," explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
The scientists have been inspired by the feet of the geckos, which are covered by microscopic hairs that give the animal a perfect hold.
Tests carried out with various materials such as glass Teflon and sandpaper have shown that the new adhesive is ten times stronger than the holding capacity of the reptiles' feet and at the same time "can be easily removed from the wall," said Liming Dai, researcher at the Faculty of Engineering at the University of Dayton.
"This material could be used as a transient adhesive," adds Liming Dai.
Perhaps it does, but the researchers are more likely to think of a less fascinating benefit, such as the connection of electrical devices, because the nanotubes are also conductors of heat and electricity.
Other areas of application could fall into the field of space travel.
So for the moment, the superheroes have to wait.
THE OTHER TYPE OF RESEARCH – also the University of Berkeley, California, is dedicated to a new type of adhesive.
In an article by the American Chemical Society, the Californian scientists present an adhesive made of microfibers that, like hair, clean themselves from dust by moving on a surface and thus always maintain perfect adhesion.
Drugs: Never take with fruit juice
Beware of grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, which are consumed mainly in summer due to their refreshing quality and vitamin abundance, can cause serious health damage when taken at the same time as certain vital drugs, as they can have an extreme effect on the body’s absorption.
David Bailey, professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, repeatedly points out the risk of both packaged and fresh fruit juices associated with medication intake. At the 236th meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he once again struck the alarm: a glass of apple, orange or grapefruit juice is enough to jeopardize the absorption capacity of certain vital drugs to such an extent that these are virtually eliminated.
Grapefruit juice has already been suspected to be responsible for increasing the effects of some drugs such as antibiotics, antiasthmatics, cardiovascular drugs, anxiolytic and neurological agents, up to toxic levels.
Drugs at Risk – The same agency of the drug had warned doctors and patients about the dangers of this mix in a report two years ago, stressing to pay attention to what is being drunk in conjunction with drugs such as Diazepan or Metadon.
It’s not just grapefruit – according to the experts, orange juice and apple juice also contain substances that can inhibit the drugs.
The list of active ingredients inhibited by the fruit juices is long.
Hence the appeal of Michele Carruba, the director of the Università Statale di Milano: "Such results are usually immediately forwarded to the various international manufacturers, who are free to change consumer information.
Therefore, it is advisable to always read the package leaflet and, if there are still ambiguities, do not be shy to ask a pharmacist or doctor," emphasizes the expert of the ANSA agency.
The Nobel Prize goes to Paul Krugman
The Nobel Prize in Economics is awarded to American Paul Krugman for his analysis of trade patterns and the establishment of economic activities.
The 55-year-old Krugman is a Neokeynesian who teaches at the University of Princeton and known for his regular articles for the New York Times.
Krugman is one of the biggest critics of the Bush administration's economic and foreign policy.
A few months after the September 11, 2001 attacks, during the days of the Enron collapse, Krugman had claimed in a New York Times editorial that this second event was more decisive for the history of the United States than the assassinations.
A prediction that received no little polemic as a response and was presented to the economist years later, but today proves to be completely correct.
"I am surprised and shocked at how quickly the memory of the scandals of the collapses of Enron or Worldcom disappeared from the public eye," Krugman said.
According to Lorenzo Bini Smaghi of the Executive Committee of the European Central Bank, Krugman is an "economist of great value," but also a banalizer with a "very aggressive style, particularly directed against the excessive liberalism of the Bush administration."
Open Office, the third version of the "Anti-Microsoft" package appears
The day of the release of OpenOffice.org 3.0 has come; the open source software as a free replacement for Microsoft’s Office is gaining an increasing number of users, both at home and in the office, both among freelancers and in the public administration.
After a year of intensive work by the voluntary developers, which is supervised by SUN Microsystems, the new Open Office now presents itself to the public with some new features: in addition to a revised and now more spartanly designed beginning menu, it has finally achieved a fundamentally guaranteed compatibility with Apple's Mac OS x operating system, as well as support for the new ODF (Open Document Format) 1.2 format, i.
Eight against was also on the compatibility with Microsoft's Office 2007, whose new formats (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx) can be read by OpenOffice.
Also interesting are some new features, such as the one that allows to reduce the size of PowerPoint presentations, which makes it easier to send e-mails, including the possibility to import PDF files into graphic editing modules while preserving the original appearance of the page.
Thus, "hybrid" PDF files can now also be generated, which extend the typical graphics of the Adobe format with the elements of a table and a word processing system.
Collaboration is one of the most improved elements of the applications: tables can now be edited multi-handedly by different users, thus avoiding conflicts in case of changes; in the case of the word processing system, each editor is assigned a Frabe to guarantee a better correction procedure.
Some companies are currently publishing various features of OpenOffice on the internet (on the cloud), while the final result is expected to be made public in the coming weeks.
The Italian version is available for download at the following link: http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html. So it follows the English version, which has been on the mirrors since Friday.
In addition to Windows and Mac OS, the program is also available for the Linux operating system.
Upon request, you can send the installation CD to your home or office.
However, freedom of charge can be an incentive for the dissemination of the program in private households, it is also in the area of business, where OpenOffice could succeed: after all, various institutions of the public administration and schools have already switched to OpenOffice.
In fact, there is not even a lack of a training offer, which means optimal help for small and medium-sized companies, and thus even opens up business prospects.
OpenOffice is made up of five main components: Writer, the Word-related text creation program; Calc, the spreadsheet program that aims to displace Excel; Impress, to create presentations like PowerPoint; Dbase to operate databases instead of the more familiar Access; and lastly, Draw, a graphics module.
