A new doping case is opened in the framework of the previous Tour de France: it is the Austrian athlete Bernhard Kohl of the Gerolsteiner team, who is third-ranked and winner of the jersey of the best climber.
The news was published by the daily L’Equipe on its website.
The 26-year-old Kohl from the Gerolsteiner team is the fourth driver to be tested positive for Cera, the third generation Epo. This was already the case with the Italians Riccardo Ricc<0xC3><0xB2> and Leonardo Piepoli as well as the German Stefan Schumacher.
The analyses from Kohl’s blood samples are among those carried out in recent weeks by the laboratories of Losanna and Chatenay-Malabry.
If the counter-tests now confirm the positive results on Cera, the Austrian will lose his third place and be excluded from the races for two years.
The head of the French anti-doping commission, Pierre Bordry, confirmed the positive epotest and, according to the Associated Press, also notified the Austrian authorities.
The 26-year-old Austrian climbed the podium behind the Spanish Carlos Sastre and the American Cadel Evans and also claimed the jersey of the best climber for himself.
THEME IMMIGRATION: THE NEW YORK TIMES QUESTION: IS ITALY racist?
Italy, "the former country of emigrants has recently become one of the preferred countries for immigrants", which are only welcomed with reluctance.
This is what the New York Times asks in a long article devoted entirely to the theme of racism in Italy, based on the case of the young Abdul William Guibre, a Burkina Faso native, who was murdered a month ago in Milan after stealing a pack of cookies.
The case bears witness to what the Times calls the "paradox of the North": the northern regions are those where "the most integration and job opportunities" exist, yet "the highest degree of anti-immigrationist sentiments and the greatest support of the Lega Nord are recorded."
As a confirmation of the growing tension between Italians and immigrants, the Times cites further episodes of intolerance from Milan, Rome, Parma, Ciampino and Castel Volturno.
And not just this.
The new legislation introduced by the League against immigration and the faster expulsion of illegal immigrants is also cited as a sign of climate change in Italy.
A movement that the Pope and the President also underline: “Giorgio Napolitano asked the Pope at a meeting on the Quirinal for a cooperation between the Church and the State to combat racism.”
Students victims of up to 900 euros per room high rental prices
The housing market for students knows no crises.
According to the latest study of the Sunia, the tenant union, a single room can cost a student up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples and 600 in Rome.
"This phenomenon has already taken on a very serious trajectory: in fact, large numbers of students are losing their right to study because their families are unable to support them at this level" - says Sunia's manager, Laura Mariani - "in these cities, the high demand from students is leading to a deformation of the market that has also damaged the other residents.
In addition, most rental offers include a number of violations: free contracts, missing registrations, no rental price limit, unauthorized sub-rents.
For the Sunia, there is a need for exceptional measures, which lead to lower rental prices through a revision of taxation.
A closer look at the study shows that in Milan a sleeping space in the Brianza district is needed for about 450 euros; a single room starts at 650 euros (in the Bande Nere district) and ends at 800 euros in the Lambiate, Udine and Fiera district or even 900 euros in the Vittoria district.
In Florence, a place to sleep costs an average of 350/400 euros, a room 700.
In Bologna, where students concentrate in the neighborhoods around the university, 250/280 euros are needed for a place to sleep, 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome, the prices in the neighborhoods around the university are around 600 euros for a single room, 450 for a sleeping place in a double room.
Only a little lower are the rents in the neighborhoods around the other universities of Rome: 550 euros in Ostiense and Cinecittà.
Only those who avoid in outskirts can save money: 300 euros for a place to sleep and 450 euros for a single room in Prenestina, Centocelle and similar quarters.
In Naples, you need 300-450 euros for a place to sleep, for a room the price is between 400 and 600 euros in the most expensive neighborhoods, the Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei.
In Bari, a place to sleep costs 250-350 euros, a single room at least 350.
In the smallest cities, prices are lower, but they have a greater weight in the urban economy.
In cities where the phenomenon of renting to non-European students is more common, such as Perugia, there is even another anomaly: rents that are 25-30% above the average are demanded by foreign students.
Goodbye to the old cinema Paradiso – the cities close their historic cinemas
The historic cinemas close due to the favoured multiplex cinemas.
“A city without cinemas is a blind city, like a face without eyes.”
This picture by the director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is currently happening in the major urban centers of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of exclusion of cinemas, which began with the birth of the large multi-room complexes in the periphery, means death for the one-room cinema in the center in the long run. A process that not only appears inevitable and irrevocable, but also carries the traits of a cultural crime.
It is like losing a friend with whom you have travelled a stretch of road full of emotions," says the director of the film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso", which earned him the Oscar and the Grand Prix of Cannes 20 years ago. It is the story of a suburban cinema and its nostalgia, which consists of living in a cinema world that is probably forever lost.
The figures provided by Anec, the central trade association, speak a clear language: in the last five years, the enormous amount of 316 traditional cinemas have had to close; these mines paid for most of the cinemas in the major cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
The most affected regions are Emilia-Romagna with 82 cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This shows that the main culprits are the multiplex cinemas, because it is precisely these three regions in which the largest number of these modern cinemas has been registered: with 195 in the last 5 years, Lombardy leads the lists, 81 are in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The business has developed in an irrational way," says Paolo Protti, the president of Anec, "it is useful that new structures also arise, but first and foremost is the preservation of what already exists, because a hall closes in the city, not all of its regular customers are willing to visit a multiplex cinema in the periphery instead of the old one.
And here remains the missing budget for the fund of the trade association: the debt burden recorded by the state is about 10 million euros.
It is a disgrace from the ethical-moral standpoint that the government fails to comply with existing laws.
In order to maintain the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros a year would be needed."
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city to decide to protect the old cinemas through an agreement between the municipality and the Anec, which is the first of its kind in Italy to protect and support the traditional cinemas, both in the historical centre and in the periphery.
Among the foreseen measures are tax advantages for the cinema operators as well as advantages for the public in terms of local transport: it will be allowed to drive to the restricted areas of the centre and also to park at lower parking fees.
"It's a pleasing initiative," says Giuseppe Tornatore, "I hope that other cities will follow our example and also design new concepts.
Certainly, however, we also need better audio and video equipment in order to be able to align against the superpower of multiplex rooms, because after all, today’s audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema has always been an important topic for me: the closure of the "Supercinema" of Baghiera, the place of my childhood and youth, was the decisive point that led me to establish the "Nuovo cinema Paradiso", even though I had been playing with the idea for 10 years.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years; when I pass by the Rialto or the Quirinale in Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn to the side so as not to have to see the dust-covered posters.
The links between politics and 'Ndrangheta lead to the arrest of the mayor of Gioia Tauro
"The mayor of Gioia Tauro was willing to adapt the decisions of the municipality to the interests of the Piromalli mafia group.
The accusations of the Calabrian anti-mafia prosecutor’s office against Mayor Giorgio Dal Torrione and his deputy Rosario Schiavone of the municipality of Gioia Tauro, who were arrested this morning for involvement in mafia business, are serious.
Handcuffed was also Gioacchino Piromalli, the older intermediary between the clan and the public administration, as well as his nephew: the lawyer, who bears the same name as the boss of the clan, had already been sentenced for involvement in criminal organizations of the mafia, then to a sum of compensation of 10 million euros.
"Disregarding any kind of moral and legal norm," the lawyers wrote, "the two local administrations had decided to pay the lawyer Piromalli funds for consulting activities."
"So it was made possible for the mafia group - according to the judges - to enter the town halls by official means and to help determine the policies of the public administration."
The president of the Calabrian Regional Committee, Agazio Loiero, does not deny that in his region "it is anything but an exception to encounter connections from local administrations and organized crime." "There are places where the concentration of the mafia is greater than in others, where such connections are virtually inevitable.
But there are also local politicians who resist the pressure of the 'Ndrangheta: heroes who get a white vest."
The arrests this morning follow those of last July, with which, according to the police, the Clan Piromalli was beheaded.
Since the end of last April, the municipal council of Gioia Tauro had been dissolved, but already in 1991 – and even then due to alleged links between organised crime and local administration – local politicians had been removed from their municipal offices.
Giorgio Dal Torrione, then mayor of the UdC, was elected head of the centre-right coalition after the second round election in May 2006.
He shouted scandal when the prefecture ordered the dissolution of the municipal council.
He addressed Vice-Minister Marco Minniti, whom he accused of inventing everything for political-strategic reasons, but the judges explained in connection with this morning’s arrest warrant that the Piromalli clan had even dared to request a change to the A3 project.
From an eavesdropping operation in connection with the investigations into the Dal Torrione case, the willingness to comply with the wishes of an entrepreneur, who is known to be a representative of the large group around the Piromalli, has been demonstrated - making the public administration's actions identical with the interests of this clan."
When the energy comes out of the waves, suddenly the big ones come up.
It is a non-drying source of money covering over 70% of the planet’s surface, and only now do the world’s big energy companies seem to understand this.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that everyone is now looking at, and are also looking to occupy, such as giants like Chevron.
The possibility of extracting energy from the movements of the sea has been considered and studied for 70 years; it is not by chance that these studies have intensified considerably since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil fell by 1980, the idea of marine energy was lost, but now the environmental organizations and the rising oil price are pushing for new impetus in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of global energy demand could be covered by the energy generated by ocean waves.
This would be twice the energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
There are also the currents and tides.
Giants in the attack.
The first company to now rely on marine energy is Enersis, which signed a contract in 2005 for the construction of a power plant in the north of Portugal.
When this news was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies from the traditional energy sector are now relying on marine energy production.
“Chevron is exploring these technologies,” said a spokesman for a company known to the American giant in the Wall Street Journal, “and is considering the possibility of working with us.”
It is about obtaining an approval from the American Energy Commission, which is necessary to start a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is a sign not to be underestimated, especially considering that in Alaska in particular, oil is still being extracted by the U.S., and President Bush has only recently set in motion plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey are also investing in the new industry; if the details are not known, observers are talking about an increasing interest.
Technologies still to be improved.
Experts speak of an emerging technology, not least because the last doubts on the part of environmentalists have not yet been clarified.
So far, projects such as this one in Portugal and Scotland are of a rather small dimension and do not seem to cause any serious environmental problems.
However, to produce energy on a large scale, technologies with a far greater impact on the environment are needed.
There are several possibilities: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of interconnected buoys.
The thrust of the shafts, which moves the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure within the floats via pistons and cylinders.
This drives a turbine, which in turn operates a generator.
The electricity is then sent to the coast via underwater pipes.
So far, there are four planned installations of this type, which are only waiting for government approval, and some of the energy obtained could also be used for military facilities.
Verdant Power is already producing energy for a department store and parking lot using undersea turbines in the East River of New York.
The water movements during the tides drive the turbines, which feed the generator due to the resulting rotary movement.
According to Verdant, a long queue of potential clients is already waiting for the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Electricity Production Research, a particular interest deserves immediately the potential that lies in the tides.
Although it is also an irregular phenomenon, the tides are better predictable than wind currents, the sunlight and also the waves, and therefore a more reliable source of electricity.
It is precisely tidal energy that has led states such as New York, Maine and Alaska, as well as other coastal states, to invest $7.5 million in 2008 – up to 35 million are already planned for 2009.
